European debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley —— "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland," people used to think, but that is no longer the case, because it is clearly a crisis of the eurozone.
Dealing with it is both easier and more difficult than usually imagined.
The economics of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has problems.
Spain has problems in all of the above three areas.
Although the details vary, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to go through a painful process of spending cuts.
The usual way to offset the side effects of austerity is to combine domestic spending cuts with depreciation of the domestic currency.
Devaluation can enhance export competitiveness, that is, substituting external demand for internal demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries, which do not have independent currencies to devalue, so they can only use internal devaluation to substitute for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have shown considerable determination to tighten their belts.
However, there is one economic variable that has not changed along with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt — except for some debt owed to junior creditors — has also remained largely unchanged.
It is this simple fact that puts the internal devaluation strategy in a self-defeating situation: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relatively.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending cuts and tax increases are needed to service the debt of the government and its guardians (such as banks).
This in turn demands more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, thus creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for the internal devaluation strategy to work, it is necessary to find a way to reduce the face value of the debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and written off when banks are insolvent.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers are reluctant to take this path.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is concerned about losing credibility in financial markets.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-downs would only burden other countries.
These concerns are not without merit, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
There are only two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose one of the two.
They unanimously ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is neither reasonable nor logical.
The operation of debt restructuring is straightforward.
The government can issue a batch of debt claims, whose face value is discounted by a certain proportion from the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose either to hold on to their bonds and redeem them at face value, but with a later maturity date and lower interest rate; or to accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than existing bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rate.
This is not cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to make it successful, there are three prerequisites.
First, it is necessary to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone has to come forward to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin American debt restructuring was implemented according to the Brady Plan, the "big brother" guarantor was the U.S. Treasury.
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, debt restructuring in one country will raise expectations in other countries, leading to a spillover effect.
Finally, the balance sheets of banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must be strengthened.
These banks need to undergo genuine stress tests, rather than the bureaucratic exercises conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring indicates a capital shortfall, a full debt-to-equity swap should be carried out for the relevant bank debts.
If this is not sufficient, the government must inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires coordinated action among countries.
Once banks' balance sheets are stabilized, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without undermining the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires strong leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that the risk exposure of German banks to the debts of peripheral Eurozone countries is significant and urgent.
They must convince the stakeholders and voters that guaranteeing public funds for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary part of an internal devaluation strategy; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should take on the responsibility of guaranteeing it without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences more severe — otherwise, disaster will follow.
Because that's just the fact.
